value.value: Workers who plan and design houses, office buildings, and other structures, make precise measurements to determine property boundaries, and/or collect, measure, and interpret geographic information to create maps and charts for political, educational, and other purposes.
An infection at an anatomic location used for vascular access.
An infection with the Cytomegalovirus that is not present from birth.
An infection with the Cytomegalovirus that is present from birth.

Workers who are responsible for the visual style of: consumer and industrial products, movie and television productions, product images in magazines and newspapers, interior design, and visual effects.
Workers who use tools, machines, and their hands to assemble finished products and the parts that go into them.
The dorsal portion of the nasopharyngeal cavity that contains the pharyngeal tonsil.
Conduct that is unusual for the individual.

label.value: Building Cleaning and Pest Control Workers

value.value: Workers who keep buildings and their surrounding grounds in clean, orderly, and good condition, and/or control unwanted creatures.

Workers whose general job duties include analyzing a business's current operations, identifying customer needs, creating reports, developing improvement plans, assisting departments in implementing changes, management and staffing, fundraising, and/or appraisals and investigations.
Workers who operate telephone business systems equipment or switchboards, and/or provide information by accessing directories, assist customers with special billing requests.

Workers who provide help and advice to people and organizations using computer software or equipment. Some support information technology (IT) employees and others assist non-IT users who are having computer problems.
A deficit in equilibrium, which may manifest as unsteady ambulation or inability to maintain an upright position.
A tradesman, laborer (an unskilled tradesman), or professional employed in the physical construction of the built environment and its infrastructure.
A laboratory test result demonstrating the presence of a specific organism in a blood sample after culture.
Laboratory results demonstrating an increase in the concentration of urea nitrogen in a blood sample.
A catheter that has moved from its intended location.
The aspect of the nasopharyngeal wall that is located on the side.  It contains the pharyngeal opening of the auditory tube.
Workers who prepare, season, and cook foods, as well as workers who perform routine tasks under the direction of cooks, chefs, or food service managers.

label.value: Counselors, Social Workers, and Other Community and Social Service Specialists

value.value: Workers who make arrangements for needed services and treatments for individuals and families and/or develop and implement specialized treatment programs within a community. Others provide front line support and social assistance for individuals, families, and communities in need.
Workers who use software to convert the designs of engineers and architects into technical drawings and plans.
A laboratory test result demonstrating the presence of antibodies that act against red blood cells.
A reduction in the normal physical activity for an individual.
Any problem with a feeding tube or its site of insertion.

label.value: Electrical and Electronic Equipment Mechanics, Installers, and Repairers

value.value: Workers who install, repair, or replace a variety of electrical equipment in telecommunications, transportation, utilities, and other industries.

A professional practitioner of engineering, concerned with applying scientific knowledge, mathematics, and ingenuity to develop solutions for technical, societal and commercial problems. Engineers design materials, structures, and systems while considering the limitations imposed by practicality, regulation, safety, and cost.

label.value: Entertainers and Performers, Sports and Related Workers

value.value: The actors, producers, directors, dancers and choreographers, musicians, singers, directors, and composers employed in the entertainment fields, as well as the athletes, coaches, scouts, managers, trainers, and umpires employed in professional sports.

The ushers, lobby attendants, ticket takers, and projectionists employed in theaters, amusement and recreation attendants, costume attendants, locker room, coatroom, and dressing room attendants, and workers in the gaming and gambling industries.
The anterior aspect of the nasopharynx.
Any worker involved in extracting resources from the ground or the sea.
Workers who do administrative work for financial institutions or within the financial industries.

Workers who meet with customers to help them determine their short-term and long-term financial goals and provide insurance, investment services, certificates of deposits and other financial instruments. They also contact prospective customers, evaluate costs and revenue, make financial presentations and review business trends.
Workers engaged in fire fighting and fire prevention and control.

label.value: First-Line Enlisted Military Supervisor and Managers

value.value: Workers who directly supervise and coordinate the activities of enlisted military personnel.

label.value: First-Line Protective Service Worker Supervisors and Managers

value.value: Workers who directly supervise and coordinate the activities of protective service workers.

label.value: Minimal Residual Disease-Based Risk Stratification in Acute Leukemia

value.value: Risk stratification of acute lymphoblastic leukemia, and less often acute myeloid leukemia, based on minimal residual disease levels.
Acute leukemia patients are stratified into the standard risk group when their minimal residual disease levels are lower than 0.05%.
Acute leukemia patients are stratified into the high risk group when their minimal residual disease levels are higher than 0.05%.
Workers who gather fish or other aquatic animals for human consumption or other uses and/or hunt and trap wild animals for human consumption, fur, feed, bait, or other purposes.
The lower part of the pharynx that connects to the esophagus.
Workers who perform a variety of customer service, food preparation, and cleaning duties in restaurants, cafeterias, and other eating and drinking establishments.
Workers who operate equipment that mixes, cooks, or processes ingredients used in the manufacturing of food.
Workers who measure and improve the quality of forests, develop, maintain, and protect forests, and/or harvest timber that provides the raw material for many consumer goods and industrial products.
Workers who organize and manage the details of a funeral.
Workers who provide a pleasant outdoor environment by ensuring that the grounds of houses, businesses, and parks are attractive, orderly, and healthy.

The group of professions that include chiropractors, dentists, dietitians and nutritionists, optometrists, pharmacists, physicians and surgeons, physicians assistants, podiatrists, registered nurses, therapists, and veterinarians.

Technicians who prepare specimens, operate automated analyzers and perform manual tests with detailed instructions, and technologists who problem solve, conduct data interpretation, establish and monitor programs, type and cross match blood samples and act as project managers.
Workers who perform basic tasks that require physical labor on construction sites.
Workers who perform routine clerical duties such as maintaining records, collecting data, and providing information to customers.
The group of professions that include bailiffs, correctional officers, and jailers; detectives and criminal investigators; fish and game wardens; parking enforcement workers; and police officers.
